'''Dr. David Herzog''', (born October 18, 1946, Newark, New Jersey) is an expert on [[eating disorders]] research and treatment.<ref name="bostonglobe">http://www.bostonglobe.com/magazine/2012/07/14/mgh-david-herzog-has-brought-eating-disorders-out-open/us1FQxNTK2FfrEY6RZEGUI/story.html</ref> He was one of the first doctors to advocate that treatments for [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]], [[Anorexia nervosa|anorexia]] and other eating disorders include both [[psychotherapy]] and [[medical]] and [[nutrition]]al monitoring,<ref name="nytimes1">http://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/12/garden/parent-child.html</ref> as well as careful follow up after patients recover.<ref name="nytimes2">http://www.nytimes.com/ref/health/healthguide/esn-eating-disorders-know.html</ref> Today he is a researcher, teacher and advocate.<ref name="www2.massgeneral">http://www2.massgeneral.org/harriscenter/about_staff.asp</ref> Much of his work has focused on changing the way the fashion industry uses models.<ref name="womensweardaily">http://www.wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-features/the-weighting-blame-3457736</ref>

==Education==
Dr. David Herzog graduated from the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]] School of Medicine in 1973. He trained in [[Pediatrics]] at the [[University of Wisconsin]], [[Madison]], and at [[Boston City Hospital]]. He trained in [[Child and Adolescent Psychiatry]] at Childrenâ€™s Hospital and Judge Baker Guidance Center in Boston, and in [[Psychiatry|General Psychiatry]] at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH).  He is Board Certified in three specialties: General Psychiatry, Child and Adolescent Psychiatry, and Pediatrics.

==Early career==
After Dr. David Herzog completed his residency in General Psychiatry at MGH in 1980, he went on the full-time staff to serve the hospital in various capacities, including Director of the Child Psychiatry Consultation-Liaison Service to Pediatrics, and Director of the Eating Disorders Unit in the Division of Child Psychiatry.

==Eating Disorder Research, Treatment and Advocacy==
Throughout his career, Dr. David Herzog has spoken out against using underage and underweight models,<ref name="womensweardaily2">http://www.wwd.com/fashion-news/designer-luxury/cfda-panel-debates-models-health-issues-2454672</ref><ref name="gforce">http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1970121561.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+25%2C+2010&author=JOAN+ANDERMAN&pub=Boston+Globe&edition=&startpage=G.5&desc=Model+of+health</ref> and supported increased intervention in the fashion industry, including from the government.<ref name="atlantic">http://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/05/what-the-us-can-and-cant-learn-from-israels-ban-on-ultra-thin-models/256891/</ref> In May 2012, Herzog helped editors of all 19 international editions of [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] take a decision to ban models that may be suffering from eating disorders or are younger than 16.<ref name="bostonglobe" />

He heads the largest longitudinal study of eating disorders in the country, in its 25th year in 2012. Dr. David Herzog has published more than 250 papers,<ref name="www2.massgeneral" /> founded or co-founded the Eating Disorders Research Society, the Academy for Eating Disorders, the [[Eating Disorders Coalition]], and the Harvard Eating Disorders Center, now the Harris Center for Education and Advocacy in Eating Disorders at MGH. 

Dr. David Herzog helped organize the annual Harris Center Public Forums, which are held every spring at Harvard University, since 1997. The forum creates dialogue about media, culture and body image, and has attracted speakers like [[Anna Wintour]], Editor of ''Vogue'', [[Diane von Furstenberg]], President of the [[Council of Fashion Designers of America]], and [[Arianna Huffington]], Editor of the [[Huffington Post]]. Dr. David Herzog also organizes, moderates or attends speaking opportunities beyond the Harris Center to raise general awareness of eating disorders and the need for more research. Speakers that Herzog has worked with include designer [[Michael Kors]] and supermodel [[Natalia Vodianova]].<ref name="huffpost">http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/02/david-herzog-eating-disorders-harris-center_n_1397895.html</ref>

Dr. David Herzog is an Endowed Professor in Psychiatry in the Field of Eating Disorders at [[Harvard Medical School]].<ref>http://nutrition.med.harvard.edu/personnel/personnel_bio.html</ref>

